defaultQ8 default&#xa0; 
defaultHeather Wheeler:default I would like to ask some questions about the fact that, for the first time, you have had the accounts qualified, and you have not got an unqualified arrangement.
default 
defaultYou are up there with 
defaultBarroso
default, so congratulations.
default 
defaultI never thought that the Department would be in the same state as 
defaultEurope
default and the Commission.
default 
defaultIt is astonishing.
default 
defaultWhat is your feeling of how that came about?
defaultSir Bob defaultKerslakedefault: Let me say, first of all, that it was very disappointing that we had these qualifications.
default 
defaultWe took the qualifications very seriously; we have conducted two internal audit reviews of the areas where we had qualifications.
default 
defaultWe have looked at them in depth, and identified how and where we need to improve how we operate.
default 
defaultI would make two points, not in any sense to reduce the significance of the qualification.
default 
defaultIt is worth saying first of all that there was no issue here of either spending outside budget or spending inappropriately that led to these qualifications.
default 
defaultThey both related to particular forms of parliamentary control totals that we breached, and those bring with them an automatic qualification.
default 
defaultThat was inevitable, but it is important to be very clear that there was no issue of either a breach in budgets or spending inappropriately.
default 
defaultI would ask David to say a few more words, if I can.
default 
defaultDavid defaultRossingtondefault: 
defaultL
defaultet me underline that point
default: t
defaulthere were two breaches.
default 
defaultThe first was to do with cash, and that was caused by not taking account of a payment that moved over from one financial year to another.
default 
defaultWe were monitoring our cash right through the year, actually very well; we were very high on the 
defaultWhitehall
default league table, but we did not have the processes in place to take account of the overhang cash from the previous year.
default 
defaultAs soon as we became aware of that, which was late in the year, we managed down spending so that the overall breach was £55 million rather than
default what it could have been—
defaultas high as £340 million.
default 
defaultThen, as Sir Bob has said, we immediately conducted an audit report and had a look at exactly what went wrong.
default 
defaultWe have got recommendations there; they will all be implemented by the end of this month, so that we do not get a recurrence.
default 
defaultThe other breach was in relation to local government 
defaultDEL
default, and that was caused by two arm’s-length bodies spending more on capital than was set out in their control total.
default 
defaultOnce again, there was no overspend overall in either of those agencies.
default 
defaultOnce again, we immediately conducted an audit investigation of what went wrong, and there were really two things that came out of that: first of all, a need for greater awareness of 
defaulthow G
defaultovernment accounting works in the arm’s-length bodies, and secondly, a need for better liaison between the Department and those arm’s-length bodies.
default 
defaultWe are actually centralising in our finance function the arrangements for sponsoring the smaller arm’s-length bodies in the departments, again, to prevent any recurrence.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ9 default&#xa0; 
defaultHeather Wheeler:default No overall overspend, two technical breaches, so nobody gets sacked?
defaultDavid defaultRossingtondefault: There are clearly systemic problems here, and it was not a case of individuals wilfully doing things wrong.
