default 
defaultWhat do you do with the data that you collect?
defaultSir Bob defaultKerslakedefault: Helen, do you want to come in on that?
defaultHelen Edwardsdefault: Part of our role is to assess where local authorities are in terms of the reductions in income and the impact it will have on them.
default 
defaultWe use the data that we get, for example, to try and skew the distribution of the grant to help those who are going to feel the effects to a large extent—so those who are particularly grant-dependent and who are not necessarily going to benefit as much from rates retention, for example.
default 
defaultWe use some of the data to do that.
default 
defaultWe use it in the assessment of spending power.
default 
defaultWe have said that we will not allow authorities’ spending power to fall below a certain amount, so that is our way of working out everything that a council gets by way of income.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ31 default&#xa0; 
defaultJames Morris:default So you see yourself playing a very active role in risk management?
default 
defaultIt is not just that it is interesting information; it will lead you to make specific interventions on local authorities.
default 
defaultIs it an interventionist role for the Department?
defaultHelen Edwardsdefault: No, it is not, in that sense.
default 
defaultBy and large, we regard it as the responsibility of local authorities to manage their own affairs and to manage them well, and, by and large, they do manage them very well.
default 
defaultHowever, as Sir Bob was saying, if a local authority appears to be getting into difficulty for whatever reason, there are a number of things that we can do.
default 
defaultOf course, we do work very closely with the Local Government Association, and they do a lot through their peer-led reviews and sector-led support.
default 
defaultThere are a number of ways in which we try to assess what is happening with particular local authorities, and if there is a need for intervention, then we will do it in different ways.
default 
defaultBy and large, it is for them to manage the risk.
defaultSir Bob defaultKerslakedefault: The way I would characterise it is that local authorities want to run their own affairs, and we believe that intervention should be an absolute last resort.
default 
defaultThe thing we do actively is to understand where local authorities are, where they might be running into difficulties, and where we might need to assist them in any way.
default 
defaultIt is about active management of 
defaultthe information, but we would be very reluctant to intervene, unless there were compelling reasons to do so.
default&#xa0;
