defaultI want to ask about the risk management modelling that was done before Help to Buy was introduced, and specifically the 20% significantly 
defaultinterest
default­
defaultfree
default loan that the Government is giving on the first part.
default 
defaultWhat modelling was done, and what assumption was made, about the future direction of house prices, given that house prices have historically been very difficult to predict?
defaultPeter Schofielddefault: The Help to Buy equity loan scheme was introduced off the back of the previous First Buy scheme, which equally offered an equity loan.
default 
defaultI would argue that it is not a free loan; it is an equity loan, so the value of the loan appreciates in line with the value of the property.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ96 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default That is the critical point: what happens in respect of new properties?
default 
defaultMany new properties are sold, and immediately they are worth 5% less than the purchase price, so what would happen if somebody were to redeem their Help to Buy loan very early on 
defaulton
default a new property?
default 
defaultWould that not involve some form of loss to the Government?
defaultPeter Schofielddefault: Not in that case, of course, because a Help to Buy equity loan requires a 5% deposit by the borrower.
default 
defaultI would also add on that that what we have seen coming into the housing market is an increase in confidence, some increase in transactions, and small increases in prices, and what we are seeing is Help to Buy being one of the factors that is helping to provide greater confidence into the housing market.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ97 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default Going back to my original question, then, what change in house prices did you allow for in your modelling when you brought the proposal forward?
defaultPeter Schofielddefault: We looked at a range of modelling, with house prices staying constant or, indeed, going up.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ98 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default What does your model tell you about house prices over the next five years?
defaultSir Bob defaultKerslakedefault: The point that Peter is making is that we did not make an assumption about where prices would go: what we did was a sensitivity analysis, to look at what would happen in terms of our investments if they went up and what would happen if they went down.
default 
defaultThat analysis then formed part of the risk assessment, which in turn addressed the issue of what we would need to cover within our budgets to cover any potential losses.
default 
defaultIt was not about the question of predictions on house prices.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ99 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default By how much would house prices need to rise for there to be no loss at all to the Government from the scheme?
defaultPeter Schofielddefault: As I say, remember that the scheme requires the borrower to put down a deposit of 5%, and that is the thing that takes the first hit in any price reduction.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ100 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default Why, in that case, is the Scrutiny Unit of the House of Commons saying that—and I quote—“the Government is relying on house prices of new-build properties included in the scheme rising by two thirds over 25 years (2% per year) to cover its own borrowing costs?”
default 
defaultDo you disagree with that?
defaultPeter Schofielddefault: I have not seen that particular report.
default 
